# 5. Count the number of NA values in a specific data frame column

# The 'is.na' function returns a logical vector with 'TRUE' in the positions where the input vector has 'NA' values.
# When used with the 'Annual_Rainfall' column of the 'agriculture' data frame, it will return a logical vector with the same length as the column, with 'TRUE' for 'NA' values and 'FALSE' otherwise.
# The 'sum' function adds up all the 'TRUE' values, effectively counting the number of 'NA' values in the 'Annual_Rainfall' column.
na_count_annual_rainfall <- sum(is.na(agriculture$Annual_Rainfall))

# Print the count of NA values in the 'Annual_Rainfall' column
na_count_annual_rainfall


#OUTPUT
> na_count_annual_rainfall
[1] 0
